This remote investigation focused on the rollover crash of a 2010 Chevrolet
Tahoe sport utility vehicle and the ejection of its unrestrained driver.  The
Chevrolet was used for law enforcement purposes and was driven by a 30-year-old
male police officer at the time of the crash.  Notification of this crash was
forwarded to the Calspan Special Crash Investigations (SCI) team on October 19,
2011 by Primary Sampling Unit (PSU) 43 of the National Automotive Sampling
System (NASS).  Calspan SCI forwarded the notification to the Crash
Investigation Division (CID) of the National Highway Traffic Safety
administration (NHTSA) and a remote combination NASS/SCI investigation was
assigned.  The remote investigation consisted of an in-depth review and analysis
of the data collected by the NASS Researcher to formulate this detailed
technical report.  The crash occurred during morning hours on a two-lane road in
a rural residential setting.  The driver steered right to avoid unspecified
debris within his travel lane and subsequently lost directional control.  As a
result, the vehicle initiated a clockwise (CW) yaw and departed the right road
edge.  The vehicle entered the roadside ditch and crossed over the private
driveway, entering the lawn of the residence.  It then tripped over its left
side tires and completed a five-quarter turn rollover sequence, coming to rest
on its left plane.  The Chevrolet was equipped with a number of safety features
including Electronic Stability Control (ESC) and a Supplemental Restraint System
with combination side impact/roll-sensing Inflatable Curtain (IC) air bags.
During the rollover crash, both the left and the right IC air bags deployed.
The driver was transported to a local hospital and admitted for the treatment of
moderate-severity lower extremity injuries.
